<cell id="cell-22"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 10 — Efficiency / Accuracy Trade-off</cell id="cell-22">
<cell id="cell-23"># Pareto plot: ATE vs inference time, colour = resolution
fig = px.scatter(
    df, x="time_s", y="ate_mean",
    text="resolution", color="resolution",
    color_continuous_scale="Viridis",
    title="Accuracy–Efficiency Trade-off (lower-left = better)",
    labels={"time_s": "Inference time (s)", "ate_mean": "ATE mean (m)"},
    size=[10] * len(df),
)
fig.update_traces(textposition="top center")
fig.show()

# Which resolution gives the best accuracy per second?
df["ate_per_sec"] = df["ate_mean"] / df["time_s"]
best_row = df.loc[df["ate_per_sec"].idxmin()]
print(f"\nBest accuracy-per-second: {int(best_row['resolution'])} px  "
      f"(ATE/s = {best_row['ate_per_sec']:.4f})")</cell id="cell-23">
<cell id="cell-24"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Discussion

### Key findings

| Resolution | Expected behaviour |
|------------|-------------------|
| 224 px     | Lowest memory/time; likely highest ATE — coarse features, poor small details |
| 336 px     | Moderate quality; good trade-off for low-VRAM GPUs |
| 518 px     | Native training resolution; lowest ATE (if pattern holds) |

### Why does ATE increase at low resolution?

VGGT uses a Vision Transformer with patch-based attention.  At lower resolutions:
- Fewer patches → less positional context for pose estimation.
- Fine texture cues (used for self-supervised pose learning) are lost.
- Depth estimation degrades, affecting the 3-D structure used indirectly
  to resolve scale.

### Connection to thesis

This analysis motivates:
1. **Adaptive resolution** (Notebook 05): run 224 px globally, patch-refine
   uncertain regions at 518 px — approaching 518-px accuracy at lower cost.
2. **Progressive refinement** (also Notebook 05): coarse-to-fine pyramid
   blending depth estimates across levels.</cell id="cell-24">
